SWINE FEVER, CLASSICAL - KOREA, SOUTH: OIE CONFIRMED
*************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 12 Oct 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties (OIE), Disease Information 11
Oct 2002 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_50.HTM#Sec6>

CLASSICAL SWINE FEVER IN KOREA (REP. OF ~)
See also: 31 May 2002, 3 May 2002, 19 Apr 2002 (Date of previous reported
outbreak: April 2002).
Emergency report: Information received on 9 Oct 2002 from Dr Hee-Woo Lee,
Director, Animal Health Division, Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry
(MAF), Seoul:
Report date: 8 Oct 2002.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, post-mortem and laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 7 Oct 2002.
Outbreaks: Location Island of Ganghwa, Incheon Metropolitan City
No. of outbreaks 1
Description of affected population: pig-fattening holding.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
species/susceptible/cases/deaths/destroyed/slaughtered
sui / 1300* / 30 / 3 / 12 / 970
* 1175 fattening pigs and 125 sows.
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: clinical inspection and laboratory
diagnosis were performed by Regional Veterinary Officers and the National
Veterinary Research and Quarantine Service, Anyang, Kyonggi.
B. Diagnostic tests used:
- direct immunofluorescence,
- NPLA(1),
- PCR(2) (5'NCR, E2, NS5B).
C. Causal agent: identification and isolation are in progress.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: not yet known.Under investigation.
B. Mode of spread: unknown.
C. Other epidemiological details: the affected holding is located in an
island remote from the mainland of the Republic of Korea.
Control measures:
- stamping-out policy;
- quarantine;
- a movement control zone has been set up within a radius of 10 km around
the infected holding;
- screening;
- vaccination is prohibited.
(1) NPLA: neutralisation peroxidase linked assay.
(2) PCR: polymerase chain reaction.
[How unfortunate! Just as South Korea was entering the required 6-month-free
time period, another outbreak occurs. See excellent comments on this year's
earlier outbreak (ref. below) for details of the requirements for a disease
free period before resumption of exports. - Mod.PC].
See Also
